article.description: Devin Harris had 13 points and nine assists to lead  Wisconsin to a 68-42 victory over Detroit on Saturday night.
article.headline: Badgers commit only eight turnovers
article.linkText: Wisconsin shoots 49 percent to crush Detroit
article.story: MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- The Wisconsin Badgers finally got their shots to drop. Freddie Owens and Devin Harris scored 13 points to lead No. 15 Wisconsin to a 68-42 victory over Detroit in Saturday night. Harris also had a career-high nine assists for the Badgers (4-1), who shot 49 percent from the field despite missing their last eight attempts after coach Bo Ryan inserted the reserves. "It was just a matter of when the shot is there, you've got to knock it down," Owens said. Wisconsin had not shot better than 38 percent in a game this season. "A lot of those same looks we've had," Ryan said. "They just didn't go down like that." Ryan credited the play of Harris, who was held to a season low in points but distributed the ball well and had no turnovers. "Devin was a big key in controlling the offensive tempo," Ryan said. "He pushed it when it was there. When it wasn't, he got the guys set." Andreas Helmigk had a career-high 12 points in his first start for the Badgers, who won their 16th straight home game. Zach Morley added 10 points and seven rebounds in a reserve role. The Badgers committed just eight turnovers and were helped by 15-for-19 shooting from the line. "Spacing was pretty good, good screens, good hard cuts, same things we've been emphasizing all along," Ryan said. "Sometimes (the shots) go down and it looks a little better." Rulon Harris scored 18 points to lead Detroit (2-2), which shot 36 percent from the field and was outrebounded 33-24 by Wisconsin. "We just got handled by a very good team," said Detroit coach Perry Watson, whose team trailed by as many as 34 points late. Wisconsin shot 60 percent from the field in the first half and led 30-20 at the break. Mike Wilkinson opened the second half with a 3-pointer, initiating a 21-7 run that helped the Badgers put the game out of reach. Detroit was held without a field goal for over seven minutes of the first half as Wisconsin used a 10-1 run to take a 19-9 lead.
